03489nam a22005895i 9780292734906DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927349067 a10.7560/7236102doi  a(DE-B1597)586661  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0220002bisacsh04a810.9/327641 aGraham, Don, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aState of Minds :bTexas Culture and Its Discontents /cDon Graham. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Ayes of Texas -- tPart One. Texas -- tPart Two. Culture -- tPart Three. Discontents -- tBibliography -- tCredits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn Steinbeck once famously wrote that "Texas is a state of mind." For those who know it well, however, the Lone Star State is more than one mind-set, more than a collection of clichés, more than a static stereotype. There are minds in Texas, Don Graham asserts, and some of the most important are the writers and filmmakers whose words and images have helped define the state to the nation, the world, and the people of Texas themselves. For many years, Graham has been critiquing Texas writers and films in the pages of Texas Monthly and other publications. In State of Minds, he brings together and updates essays he published between 1999 and 2009 to paint a unique, critical picture of Texas culture. In a strong personal voice—wry, humorous, and ironic—Graham offers his take on Texas literary giants ranging from J. Frank Dobie to Larry McMurtry and Cormac McCarthy and on films such as The Alamo, The Last Picture Show, and Brokeback Mountain. He locates the works he discusses in relation to time and place, showing how they sprang (or not) from the soil of Texas and thereby helped to define Texas culture for generations of readers and viewers—including his own younger self growing up on a farm in Collin County. Never shying from controversy and never dull, Graham's essays in State of Minds demolish the notion that "Texas culture" is an oxymoron.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72361040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292734906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292734906/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK